// SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception
//
// test/preprocess/p02/pass.test — P2 narrower-than-C identifier
// passthrough per `docs/spec/nsl_pp.ebnf` notes section, and the
// "Validation tests" topic table in
// `specs/002-m1-lex-preprocess/contracts/preprocessor-seam.contract.md`.
//
// Topic per the table: "passthrough: identifiers on non-directive
// lines NOT macro-expanded (only `%IDENT%` and helper-call sites
// are)". This is P2's narrower-than-C semantics: even though `module`
// might be a `#define`'d macro name in some build configurations,
// a bare-identifier reference on a passthrough line MUST NOT be
// macro-expanded — only the explicit `%IDENT%` reference form (P3)
// triggers expansion.
//
// Pass shape:
//   line 1: `#define module foo`   — macro defining `module` to `foo`
//   line 2: `module bar { }`       — bare `module` on a passthrough
//                                    line; per P2 it stays as the
//                                    keyword `tk_module`, NOT
//                                    expanded to `foo`.
//
// This catches a "leaky C-cpp" implementation that walks every
// passthrough line scanning each identifier through the macro
// table — a P2 violation that would let `#define` redefine NSL
// keywords.
//
// Tasks.md T038: pass-only — fail-case is N/A (invariant; you can't
// "violate" P2 from source-level by writing a bare identifier).
//
// **RED state**: against the unchanged Phase-3 tree the lexer sees
// `#define module foo` literally and tokenizes the directive bytes
// — Phase-4 makes the column-0 `#define` consumption real.

// RUN: echo '#define module foo' >  %t.nsl
// RUN: echo 'module bar { }'     >> %t.nsl
// RUN: %nslc -emit=tokens %t.nsl | FileCheck %s

// Line 2 emits `tk_module` (the keyword), NOT `tk_identifier foo`.
// CHECK:      tk_module{{[ \t]+}}module
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_identifier{{[ \t]+}}bar
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_lbrace{{[ \t]+}}{
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_rbrace{{[ \t]+}}}
// CHECK-NEXT: tk_eof

// And the macro replacement TEXT (`foo`) must not have leaked into
// the seam:
// CHECK-NOT: tk_identifier{{[ \t]+}}foo
